# zero-touchd — device control + gNMI provisioning over SMS.
#
# The daemon consumes the MT-SMS envelope cellular-client publishes and answers
# with a single MO SMS. It is INERT until zerotouch.enabled=true.
#
# Behaviour is driven by ds keys, not by this file — they hot-apply on change:
#
#   ds-cli set zerotouch.enabled true
#   ds-cli set zerotouch.gnmi.port 50051
#   ds-cli set zerotouch.allowed.numbers '"+919096383701,+4915112345678"'
#   ds-cli set zerotouch.session.ttl.sec 600
#
# Command grammar (text these to the device's SIM number; IOT LOGIN first):
#
#   IOT LOGIN <user> <password>              # users are the device-ui users
#   IOT GNMI GET /system/config/hostname     # Viewer session
#   IOT GNMI GET /a,/b                        # comma-separated xpaths
#   IOT GNMI SET /system/config/hostname r7   # Admin session (mutating)
#   IOT GNMI SET /a,/b 1,2                    # positional xpath/value pairing
#   IOT LOGOUT
#   ...plus the classic smsctl commands (STATUS/WIFI/APN/REBOOT/FACTORY-RESET).
#
# SECURITY:
#   - The login password crosses the carrier in PLAINTEXT. Prefer a dedicated
#     Admin account for SMS over the shared `admin` one.
#   - A gNMI GET reply also crosses in plaintext; sensitive paths
#     (password/psk/secret/…) are denied at the daemon and never returned.
#   - Set zerotouch.allowed.numbers so unknown senders are dropped without a reply.
#   - gNMI GET/SET always target 127.0.0.1 — the host is never taken from the SMS.
#
# Args are optional; the ds keys are the real control surface.
#   --ds-sock=PATH   ds-server unix socket (default: built-in)
ZEROTOUCH_ARGS=""
